1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,490
In this demo, we'll introduce a few scikit-learn

2
00:00:02,490 --> 00:00:05,670
preprocessing tools for key parts of the data cleaning process;

3
00:00:05,670 --> 00:00:08,730
scaling, encoding, and imputing missing values.

4
00:00:08,730 --> 00:00:12,090
Let's start our demo by importing the sklearn package.

5
00:00:12,090 --> 00:00:16,050
I'm also going to import a couple of methods from sklearn and NumPy.

6
00:00:16,050 --> 00:00:19,050
I'm also going to import the set config function

7
00:00:19,050 --> 00:00:22,110
from sklearn setting transform output equals

8
00:00:22,110 --> 00:00:27,960
Pandas so that outputs from the sklearn package of transform and fit transform functions,

9
00:00:27,960 --> 00:00:29,115
which we'll look at in a moment,

10
00:00:29,115 --> 00:00:31,380
will be in the Pandas DataFrame format.

11
00:00:31,380 --> 00:00:33,780
We'll see what this looks like in just a moment.

12
00:00:33,780 --> 00:00:36,450
Let's now turn to one of the fundamental steps to

13
00:00:36,450 --> 00:00:38,950
do for cleaning your data, standardizing it.

14
00:00:38,950 --> 00:00:40,955
In many real-world cases,

15
00:00:40,955 --> 00:00:45,895
the scale or range that applies for one variable in our dataset doesn't apply to others.

16
00:00:45,895 --> 00:00:48,290
For example, one column in your data can contain

17
00:00:48,290 --> 00:00:51,020
values around blood pressure measurements like ranging from

18
00:00:51,020 --> 00:00:54,500
120-150 systolic and another column contains values

19
00:00:54,500 --> 00:00:58,295
around patients income ranging 20,000-100,000.

20
00:00:58,295 --> 00:01:00,770
The large differences in the scale of values for

21
00:01:00,770 --> 00:01:03,095
these variables can make many tasks challenging,

22
00:01:03,095 --> 00:01:04,955
especially machine learning tasks.

23
00:01:04,955 --> 00:01:06,620
We should ensure our data follows

24
00:01:06,620 --> 00:01:10,070
a standard scale and can be easily used to train ML models.

25
00:01:10,070 --> 00:01:12,545
We call this scaling data.

26
00:01:12,545 --> 00:01:17,060
A a popular form of being able to scale data for a given data sample

27
00:01:17,060 --> 00:01:21,080
is removing the mean and scaling the distribution to unit variance.

28
00:01:21,080 --> 00:01:23,030
Take a look at a short snippet here that's

29
00:01:23,030 --> 00:01:25,430
borrowed from one of sklearn's create tutorials.

30
00:01:25,430 --> 00:01:29,840
Here we create an array using NumPy with some random numbers in it.

31
00:01:29,840 --> 00:01:33,290
Now we can apply sklearn's standard scaler to

32
00:01:33,290 --> 00:01:36,815
scale the data and we fit it on our tiny dataset.

33
00:01:36,815 --> 00:01:41,620
Fitting computes the mean and standard deviation to be used for later scaling.

34
00:01:41,620 --> 00:01:43,635
Let's go ahead and run this.

35
00:01:43,635 --> 00:01:46,340
Now we can go ahead and print the mean and

36
00:01:46,340 --> 00:01:48,410
the standard deviation that were generated

37
00:01:48,410 --> 00:01:50,720
for the data using the corresponding attributes.

38
00:01:50,720 --> 00:01:53,570
Finally, we can apply the transform function,

39
00:01:53,570 --> 00:01:55,400
which is actually performing the scaling

40
00:01:55,400 --> 00:01:58,010
using the values prepared during the bidding stage.

41
00:01:58,010 --> 00:02:03,245
There's also a way to fit and transform in one command called fit_transform.

42
00:02:03,245 --> 00:02:05,780
Now, after doing the transform function,

43
00:02:05,780 --> 00:02:09,400
we see that the scale data has zero mean and unit variance.

44
00:02:09,400 --> 00:02:12,755
There are additional types of scalers that sklearn is offering,

45
00:02:12,755 --> 00:02:15,020
like the minmax scaler to scale variables to

46
00:02:15,020 --> 00:02:17,450
lie between a given minimum and maximum value,

47
00:02:17,450 --> 00:02:19,370
often between zero and one.

48
00:02:19,370 --> 00:02:22,885
There's also methods to scale values that have outliers.

49
00:02:22,885 --> 00:02:26,120
Encoding is a popular technique for many reasons,

50
00:02:26,120 --> 00:02:29,885
including transforming categorical data into numerical data.

51
00:02:29,885 --> 00:02:32,360
One of these techniques is ordinal encoding,

52
00:02:32,360 --> 00:02:35,990
which encodes data and categorical features as an integer array.

53
00:02:35,990 --> 00:02:39,440
Let's consider this really tiny dataset with three words;

54
00:02:39,440 --> 00:02:40,730
data, wrangling, rocks.

55
00:02:40,730 --> 00:02:45,955
We can define an ordinal encoder and apply a fit transform to this tiny dataset.

56
00:02:45,955 --> 00:02:49,960
We can see it assigned the value of zero to the word data,

57
00:02:49,960 --> 00:02:51,170
two to the word wrangling,

58
00:02:51,170 --> 00:02:52,790
and one to the word rocks.

59
00:02:52,790 --> 00:02:55,370
Now there's another option for encoding these types of

60
00:02:55,370 --> 00:02:57,930
variables that's popular and that's known as one-hot encoding.

61
00:02:57,930 --> 00:03:02,395
This actually encodes categorical features as a one-hot numeric array.

62
00:03:02,395 --> 00:03:05,385
On our same simple dataset, data, wrangling, rocks,

63
00:03:05,385 --> 00:03:08,545
note how three columns now created for each of the three words.

64
00:03:08,545 --> 00:03:11,415
The word data is represented as 100,

65
00:03:11,415 --> 00:03:14,470
the word wrangling is represented as 010,

66
00:03:14,470 --> 00:03:17,555
and the word rocks is represented as 001.

67
00:03:17,555 --> 00:03:22,150
This makes it easier for computers to understand categorical data and text data.

68
00:03:22,150 --> 00:03:24,590
Finally, after scaling and encoding,

69
00:03:24,590 --> 00:03:27,250
let's look at how to impute missing values in scikit-learn.

70
00:03:27,250 --> 00:03:30,980
This code block is written in Python and uses the scikit-learn library.

71
00:03:30,980 --> 00:03:32,540
We fetched the Titanic dataset from

72
00:03:32,540 --> 00:03:36,410
the open ML repository using the function fetch_openml,

73
00:03:36,410 --> 00:03:39,510
which downloads datasets from our open ML repo.

74
00:03:39,510 --> 00:03:43,160
In this case, our code snippet is actually downloading the Titanic dataset with

75
00:03:43,160 --> 00:03:48,055
Version 1 as a Pandas DataFrame and storing it in variables x and y.

76
00:03:48,055 --> 00:03:50,570
We're then going to use the function train_test_split,

77
00:03:50,570 --> 00:03:53,390
which is used to split data into training and test sets that are

78
00:03:53,390 --> 00:03:56,960
typically used to train and test machine learning models respectively.

79
00:03:56,960 --> 00:04:00,080
The stratify parameter ensures that the proportion of classes

80
00:04:00,080 --> 00:04:03,400
in the original data is preserved in both training and test sets.

81
00:04:03,400 --> 00:04:07,490
Let's briefly understand what this data is taking a peek at the first few rows.

82
00:04:07,490 --> 00:04:11,735
The Titanic dataset is a popular dataset used in machine learning and data science.

83
00:04:11,735 --> 00:04:15,500
The x dataframe here is containing info about passengers on the Titanic,

84
00:04:15,500 --> 00:04:17,450
like their name, age, and gender.

85
00:04:17,450 --> 00:04:22,595
The data series in y is containing info on whether or not these individuals survived.

86
00:04:22,595 --> 00:04:26,060
Zero means they didn't survive and one means they did survive.

87
00:04:26,060 --> 00:04:30,185
Notice how the variables are of different datatypes somewhere numbers,

88
00:04:30,185 --> 00:04:34,400
continuous variables other represent categories like categorical variables.

89
00:04:34,400 --> 00:04:39,320
Now let's look at a number of missing values in each column of the x_test DataFrame.

90
00:04:39,320 --> 00:04:43,220
We can skip over to the isnull function which returns a Boolean DataFrame

91
00:04:43,220 --> 00:04:47,075
